04676nam a22006975i 9780226390901DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263909017 a10.7208/97802263909012doi  a(DE-B1597)524235  a(OCoLC)963934712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHD9665.5b.T46 2017 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a303.48322300aTherapeutic Revolutions :bPharmaceuticals and Social Change in the Twentieth Century /cFlurin Condrau, Jeremy A. Greene, Elizabeth Siegel Watkins. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b4 halftones, 8 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Medicine Made Modern by Medicines -- t1. Futures and their Uses -- t2. Reconceiving the Pill -- t3. Magic Bullet in the Head? -- t4. Revolutionary Markets? -- t5. Recurring Revolutions? -- t6. Pharmaceutical Geographies -- t7. After McKeown -- t8. Chemotherapy in the Shadow of Antiretrovirals -- t9. Volatility, Speculation, and Therapeutic Revolutions in Nigerian Drug Markets -- t10. Therapeutic Evolution or Revolution? -- t11. A Therapeutic Revolution Revisited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen asked to compare the practice of medicine today to that of a hundred years ago, most people will respond with a story of therapeutic revolution: Back then we had few effective remedies, but now we have more (and more powerful) tools to fight disease, from antibiotics to psychotropics to steroids to anticancer agents. This collection challenges the historical accuracy of this revolutionary narrative and offers instead a more nuanced account of the process of therapeutic innovation and the relationships between the development of medicines and social change. These assembled histories and ethnographies span three continents and use the lived experiences of physicians and patients, consumers and providers, and marketers and regulators to reveal the tensions between universal claims of therapeutic knowledge and the actual ways these claims have been used and understood in specific sites, from postwar West Germany pharmacies to twenty-first century Nigerian street markets. By asking us to rethink a story we thought we knew, Therapeutic Revolutions offers invaluable insights to historians, anthropologists, and social scientists of medicine.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPharmaceutical industryxSocial aspects. 0aTherapeuticsxSocial aspects. 4abiomedicine. 4aconsumer history. 4ahistory of medicine. 4ahistory of science. 4amedical anthropology. 4amodern medicine. 4apharmaceutical industry. 4aprescription drugs. 4atherapeutic revolution. 4atwentieth century history. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aCondrau, Flurin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreene, Jeremy A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWatkins, Elizabeth Siegel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226390901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226390901.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles